[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] In software engineering, the **active record pattern** is an architectural pattern.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] It is found in software that stores in-memory object data in relational databases.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] It was named by Martin Fowler in his 2003 book *Patterns of Enterprise Application Architecture*.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] The interface of an object conforming to this pattern would include functions such as Insert, Update, and Delete, plus properties that correspond more or less directly to the columns in the underlying database table.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] The Active Record pattern is a Data Access Layer that performs bidirectional transfer of data between a persistent data store (often a relational database) and an in-memory data representation (the domain layer).
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] A database table or view is wrapped into a class.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] Thus, an object instance is tied to a single row in the table.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] After creation of an object, a new row is added to the table upon save.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] Any object loaded gets its information from the database.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] When an object is updated, the corresponding row in the table is also updated.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] The wrapper class implements accessor methods or properties for each column in the table or view.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] This pattern is commonly used by object persistence tools and in object–relational mapping (ORM).
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] Typically, foreign key relationships will be exposed as an object instance of the appropriate type via a property.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] Implementations of the concept can be found in various frameworks for many programming environments.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] This will find a new `Part` object based on the first matching row from the `parts` table whose `name` column has the value "gearbox".
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] Various libraries implement an active record pattern framework, such as POCO C++ Libraries in library `Poco::ActiveRecord`.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] This is a simple example of an active record object `User`, in Java.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] Here the `User` class is both the model and data access object and provides `save()`, `find()`, and `delete()` methods.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] Another critique of the active record pattern is that, due to the strong coupling of database interaction and application logic, an active record object does not follow the single responsibility principle and separation of concerns.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] This is opposed to multitier architecture, which properly addresses these practices.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] Because of this, the active record pattern is best and most often employed in simple applications that are all forms-over-data with CRUD functionality, or only as one part of an architecture.
[src:adonisjs-node/active-record-pattern] Typically that part is data access and why several ORMs implement the active record pattern.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] AdonisJS is a **backend-first, type-safe framework** for building web applications with Node.js and TypeScript.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] It provides the core building blocks for writing and maintaining complete backends, eliminating the need for third-party services to handle **common features such as authentication, file uploads, caching, and rate limiting**.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] Each AdonisJS application is written in TypeScript, runs in ESM mode, and offers end-to-end type safety across the entire stack.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] AdonisJS is designed for developers building production web applications who need more structure than Express but less ceremony than enterprise frameworks.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] If you're building REST APIs, server-rendered applications, or full-stack web apps, and you value conventions over configuration, AdonisJS will feel natural.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] If you're coming from Laravel, Rails, or Django, you'll recognize the MVC patterns and conventions.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] If you've worked with Express or Fastify, you'll appreciate having structure and batteries included without sacrificing simplicity.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] AdonisJS provides the structure, consistency, and tooling expected from a full-featured framework, while remaining lightweight and modern in design.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] AdonisJS is designed to provide everything you need for real-world backend applications, while remaining approachable and easy to configure.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] Whether you're building a startup MVP or a production system serving thousands of users, AdonisJS provides the foundation without getting in your way.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] Many frameworks introduce enterprise abstractions that complicate projects without adding clarity.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] AdonisJS focuses on a different approach.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] It offers a **practical development model** that focuses on clarity, type safety, and maintainability rather than patterns for their own sake.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] The framework encourages good structure through conventions but never enforces heavy architectural layers.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] The framework includes batteries such as routing, middleware, validation, and ORM out of the box, allowing teams to focus on application logic instead of building common patterns repeatedly.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] AdonisJS APIs are functional and modern.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] You can use class-based components where a structured approach is helpful, such as in controllers, models, and services.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] Choose AdonisJS when you want the productivity of a full-featured framework without the complexity of enterprise patterns or the fragmentation of minimal frameworks.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] AdonisJS uses the **Model-View-Controller (MVC)** pattern to keep data, logic, and presentation separate.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] The view layer is optional and can be configured to fit your needs.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] Most backend code, such as routing, controllers, models, and middleware, stays the same no matter how you render views.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] This flexibility allows you to start with server-side rendering and transition to a modern SPA setup later, without modifying your core backend logic.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] AdonisJS has been in active development since 2015, with version 7 representing years of real-world usage and refinement.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] The framework is maintained by its creator full-time, with support from the core team members and an active community.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] The ecosystem includes official packages for common backend needs, all maintained by the core team with the same quality standards.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] Community packages extend functionality for specific needs like payment processing, cloud storage, and third-party integrations.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] All documentation, tooling, and packages follow semantic versioning, ensuring stable upgrades and long-term maintainability.
[src:adonisjs-node/introduction] Understand AdonisJS's approach to frontend development and choose between Hypermedia, Inertia, and API-only stacks for your application.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:adonisjs-node/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js allows developers to use JavaScript for writing command line tools and server-side scripting.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Running Javascript on the server is commonly used to generate dynamic web page content before the page is sent to the user's web browser.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Consequently, Node.js represents a "JavaScript everywhere" paradigm, unifying web-application development around a single programming language, as opposed to using different languages for the server- versus client-side programming.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js has an event-driven architecture capable of asynchronous I/O.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] These design choices aim to optimize throughput and scalability in web applications with many input/output operations, as well as for real-time Web applications (e.g., real-time communication programs and browser games).
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The Node.js distributed development project was previously governed by the Node.js Foundation, and has now merged with the JS Foundation to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] OpenJS Foundation is facilitated by the Linux Foundation's Collaborative Projects program.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js was initially written by Ryan Dahl in 2009, about 13 years after the introduction of the first server-side JavaScript environment, Netscape's LiveWire Pro Web.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The initial release supported only Linux and Mac OS X.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Its development and maintenance was led by Dahl and later sponsored by Joyent.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Dahl demonstrated the project at the inaugural European JSConf on November 8, 2009.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js combined Google's V8 JavaScript engine, an event loop, and a low-level I/O API.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] In January 2010, a package manager was introduced for the Node.js environment called npm.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The package manager allows programmers to publish and share Node.js packages, along with the accompanying source code, and is designed to simplify the installation, update and uninstallation of packages.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] In June 2011, Microsoft and Joyent implemented a native Windows version of Node.js.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The first Node.js build supporting Windows was released in July 2011.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] In January 2012, Dahl yielded management of the project to npm creator Isaac Schlueter.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] In January 2014, Schlueter announced that Timothy J.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] In December 2014, Fedor Indutny created io.js, a fork of Node.js created because of dissatisfaction with Joyent's governance as an open-governance alternative with a separate technical committee.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The goal was to enable a structure that would be more receptive to community input, including the updating of io.js with the latest Google V8 JavaScript engine releases, diverging from Node.js's approach at that time.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The Node.js Foundation, formed to reconcile Node.js and io.js under a unified banner, was announced in February 2015.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The merger was realized in September 2015 with Node.js v0.12 and io.js v3.3 combining into Node v4.0.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] This merge brought V8 ES6 features into Node.js and started a long-term support release cycle.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] By 2016, the io.js website recommended returning to Node.js and announced no further io.js releases, effectively ending the fork and solidifying the merger's success.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] In 2019, the JS Foundation and Node.js Foundation merged to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The Node.js logo features a green hexagon with overlapping bands to represent the cross-platform nature of the runtime.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The Rocket Turtle was chosen as the official Node.js mascot in February 2024 following a design contest.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js allows the creation of web servers and networking tools using JavaScript and a collection of "modules" that handle various core functionalities.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Modules are provided for file system I/O, networking (DNS, HTTP, TCP, TLS/SSL or UDP), binary data (buffers), cryptography functions, data streams and other core functions.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js's modules use an API designed to reduce the complexity of writing server applications.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Since version 22.6.0, Node.js natively supports both JavaScript and TypeScript, allowing TypeScript files to be executed without a separate compilation step.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The TypeScript support was contributed by Node.js TSC member Marco Ippolito.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] In addition, many compile-to-JS languages are available, allowing Node.js applications to also be written in CoffeeScript, Dart, ClojureScript, and others.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js is primarily used to build network programs such as web servers.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The most significant difference between Node.js and PHP is that most functions in PHP block until completion (commands execute only after previous commands finish), while Node.js functions are non-blocking (commands execute concurrently and use callbacks to signal completion or failure).
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js is officially supported by Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows 8.1 and Server 2012 (and later), with Tier 2 support for SmartOS and IBM AIX and experimental support for FreeBSD.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] OpenBSD also works, and LTS versions are available for IBM i (AS/400).
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The source code may also be built on similar operating systems that are not officially supported, such as NonStop OS and Unix servers.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js enables development of fast web servers in JavaScript using event-driven programming.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Developers can create scalable servers without using threading by using a simplified model that uses callbacks to signal the completion of a task.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js connects the ease of a scripting language (JavaScript) with the power of Unix network programming.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js was built on top of Google's V8 JavaScript engine since it was open-sourced under the BSD license, and it contains comprehensive support for fundamental protocols such as HTTP, DNS and TCP.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] JavaScript's existing popularity made Node.js accessible to the web-development community.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] There are thousands of open-source libraries for Node.js, most of which are hosted on the npm website.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Multiple developer conferences and events are held that support the Node.js community, including NodeConf, Node Interactive, and Node Summit, as well as a number of regional events.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The open-source community has developed web frameworks to accelerate the development of applications.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Such frameworks include Express.js, Socket.IO, Sails.js, Next.js and Meteor.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Various packages have also been created for interfacing with other languages or runtime environments such as Microsoft .NET.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Modern desktop IDEs provide editing and debugging features specifically for Node.js applications.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Such IDEs include Atom, Brackets, JetBrains WebStorm, Microsoft Visual Studio (with Node.js Tools for Visual Studio, or TypeScript with Node definitions), NetBeans, Nodeclipse Enide Studio (Eclipse-based) and Visual Studio Code.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Some online IDEs also support Node.js, such as Codeanywhere, Eclipse Che, Cloud9 IDE and the visual flow editor in Node-RED.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js is supported across a number of cloud-hosting platforms such as Jelastic, Google Cloud Platform, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Azure Web Apps and Joyent.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] New major releases of Node.js are cut from the GitHub main branch every six months.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Even-numbered versions are cut in April and odd-numbered versions are cut in October.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] When a new odd version is released, the previous even version undergoes transition to Long Term Support (LTS), which gives that version 12 months of active support from the date it is designated LTS.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] After these 12 months expire, an LTS release receives an additional 18 months of maintenance support.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] An active version receives non-breaking backports of changes a few weeks after they land in the current release.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] A maintenance release receives only critical fixes and documentation updates.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The LTS Working Group manages strategy and policy in collaboration with the Technical Steering Committee of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment that processes incoming requests in a loop, called the event loop.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js uses libuv under the hood to handle asynchronous events.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Libuv is an abstraction layer for network and file system functionality on both Windows and POSIX-based systems such as Linux, macOS, OSS on NonStop, and Unix.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js relies on nghttp2 for HTTP support.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] As of version 20, Node.js uses the ada library which provides up-to-date WHATWG URL compliance.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] As of version 19.5, Node.js uses the simdutf library for fast Unicode validation and transcoding.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] As of version 21.3, Node.js uses the simdjson library for fast JSON parsing.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js operates on a single-thread event loop, using non-blocking I/O calls, allowing it to support tens of thousands of concurrent connections without incurring the cost of thread context switching.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The design of sharing a single thread among all the requests that use the observer pattern is intended for building highly concurrent applications, where any function performing I/O must use a callback.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] To accommodate the single-threaded event loop, Node.js uses the libuv library—which, in turn, uses a fixed-sized thread pool that handles some of the non-blocking asynchronous I/O operations.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] A thread pool handles the execution of parallel tasks in Node.js.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The main thread function call posts tasks to the shared task queue, which threads in the thread pool pull and execute.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Inherently non-blocking system functions such as networking translate to kernel-side non-blocking sockets, while inherently blocking system functions such as file I/O run in a blocking way on their own threads.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] When a thread in the thread pool completes a task, it informs the main thread of this, which in turn, wakes up and executes the registered callback.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] A downside of this single-threaded approach is that Node.js does not allow vertical scaling by increasing the number of CPU cores of the machine it is running on without using an additional module, such as cluster, StrongLoop Process Manager, or pm2.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] However, developers can increase the default number of threads in the libuv thread pool.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The server operating system (OS) is likely to distribute these threads across multiple cores.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Another problem is that long-lasting computations and other CPU-bound tasks freeze the entire event-loop until completion.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] V8 is the JavaScript execution engine which was initially built for Google Chrome.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] It was then open-sourced by Google in 2008.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Written in C++, V8 compiles JavaScript source code to native machine code at runtime.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] As of 2016, it also includes Ignition, a bytecode interpreter.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] npm is the pre-installed package manager for the Node.js server platform.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] It installs Node.js programs from the npm registry, organizing the installation and management of third-party Node.js programs.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js registers with the operating system so the OS notifies it of asynchronous I/O events such as new connections.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Within the Node.js runtime, events trigger callbacks and each connection is handled as a small heap allocation.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Traditionally, relatively heavyweight OS processes or threads handled each connection.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js uses an event loop for concurrent I/O, instead of processes or threads.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] In contrast to other event-driven servers, Node.js's event loop does not need to be called explicitly.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Instead, callbacks are defined, and the server automatically enters the event loop at the end of the callback definition.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js exits the event loop when there are no further callbacks to be performed.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js supports WebAssembly and as of Node 14 has experimental support of WASI, the WebAssembly System Interface.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Node.js provides a way to create "add-ons" via a C-based API called N-API, which can be used to produce loadable (importable) `.node` modules from source code written in C/C++.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The modules can be directly loaded into memory and executed from within JS environment as simple CommonJS modules.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The implementation of the N-API relies on internal C/C++ Node.js and V8 objects requiring users to import (#include) Node.js specific headers into their native source code.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] As the Node.js API is subject to breaking changes at a binary level, modules have to be built and shipped against specific Node.js versions to work properly.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] To address the issue, third parties have introduced open-sourced С/С++ wrappers on top of the API that partially alleviate the problem.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] They simplify interfaces, but as a side effect they may also introduce complexity which maintainers have to deal with.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Even though the core functionality of Node.js resides in a JavaScript built-in library, modules written in C++ can be used to enhance capabilities and to improve performance of applications.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] In order to produce such modules one needs to have an appropriate C++ compiler and necessary headers (the latter are typically shipped with Node.js itself), e.g., gcc, clang or MSVC++.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The N-API is similar to Java Native Interface.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] OpenHarmony and ArkTS also adopts N-API, with the internal implementation rewritten.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] In 2015, various branches of the greater Node.js community began working under the vendor-neutral Node.js Foundation.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The Node.js Foundation Technical Steering Committee (TSC) is the technical governing body of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The TSC is responsible for the core Node.js repo as well as dependent and adjacent projects.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Generally the TSC delegates the administration of these projects to working groups or committees.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] The LTS group that manages long term supported releases is one such group.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] Other current groups include Website, Streams, Build, Diagnostics, i18n, Evangelism, Docker, Addon API, Benchmarking, Post-mortem, Intl, Documentation, and Testing.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] In August 2017, a third of the TSC members resigned due to a dispute related to the project's code of conduct.
[src:adonisjs-node/node-js] They resigned after a vote failed to remove a member from the leadership group against whom multiple complaints had been filed.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] TypeScript may be used to develop JavaScript applications for both client-side and server-side execution (as with React.js, Node.js, Deno or Bun).
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] Multiple options are available for transpiling.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] The default TypeScript Compiler can be used, or the Babel compiler can be invoked to convert TypeScript to JavaScript.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] TypeScript supports definition files that can contain type information of existing JavaScript libraries, much like C++ header files can describe the structure of existing object files.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] This enables other programs to use the values defined in the files as if they were statically typed TypeScript entities.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] There are third-party header files for popular libraries such as jQuery, MongoDB, and D3.js.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] TypeScript headers for the Node.js library modules are also available, allowing development of Node.js programs within TypeScript.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] The TypeScript compiler is written in TypeScript and compiled to JavaScript.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] It is licensed under the Apache License 2.0.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] Anders Hejlsberg, lead architect of C# and creator of Delphi and Turbo Pascal, has worked on developing TypeScript.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] TypeScript was released to the public in October 2012, with version 0.8, after two years of internal development at Microsoft.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] Soon after the initial public release, Miguel de Icaza praised the language, but criticized the lack of mature integrated development environment (IDE) support apart from Microsoft Visual Studio, which was unavailable then on Linux and macOS.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] As of April 2021 there is support in other IDEs and text editors, including Emacs, Vim, WebStorm, Atom and Microsoft's own Visual Studio Code.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] TypeScript 0.9, released in 2013, added support for generics.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] TypeScript 1.0 was released at Microsoft's Build developer conference in 2014.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] Visual Studio 2013 Update 2 provided built-in support for TypeScript.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] Further improvement were made in July 2014, when the development team announced a new TypeScript compiler, asserted to have a five-fold performance increase.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] Simultaneously, the source code, which was initially hosted on CodePlex, was moved to GitHub.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] On 22 September 2016, TypeScript 2.0 was released, introducing several features, including the ability for programmers to optionally enforce null safety.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] TypeScript 3.0 was released on 30 July 2018, bringing many language additions like tuples in rest parameters and spread expressions, rest parameters with tuple types, generic rest parameters and so on.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] TypeScript 4.0 was released on 20 August 2020.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] While 4.0 did not introduce any breaking changes, it added language features such as Custom JSX Factories and Variadic Tuple Types.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] TypeScript 5.0 was released on 16 March 2023 and included support for decorators.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] On March 11, 2025, Anders Hejlsberg announced on the TypeScript blog that the team is working on a Go port of the TypeScript compiler to be released as TypeScript version 7.0 later this year.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] It is expected to feature a 10x speedup.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] On December 2nd, 2025, Daniel Rosenwasser announced on the blog that TypeScript 6.0 will be the last release written in TypeScript itself, and TypeScript 7.0 will be the first Go-based release.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] TypeScript originated from the shortcomings of JavaScript for developing large-scale applications both at Microsoft and among their external customers.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] Challenges with dealing with complex JavaScript code led to demand for custom tooling to ease developing of components in the language.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] Developers sought a solution that would not break compatibility with the ECMAScript (ES) standard and its ecosystem, so a compiler was developed to transform a superset of JavaScript with type annotations and classes (TypeScript files) back into vanilla ECMAScript 5 code.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] TypeScript classes were based on the then-proposed ECMAScript 6 class specification to make writing prototypal inheritance less verbose and error-prone, and type annotations enabled IntelliSense and improved tooling.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] Syntactically, TypeScript is very similar to JScript .NET, another Microsoft implementation of the ECMA-262 language standard that added support for static typing and classical object-oriented language features such as classes, inheritance, interfaces, and namespaces.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] As TypeScript is simply a superset of JavaScript, existing JavaScript can be adapted to TypeScript and TypeScript program can seamlessly consume JavaScript.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] The compiler can target all ECMAScript versions 5 and above, transpiling modern features like classes and arrow functions to their older counterparts.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] With TypeScript, it is possible to use existing JavaScript code, incorporate popular JavaScript libraries, and call TypeScript-generated code from other JavaScript.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] Type declarations for these libraries are usually provided with the source code but can be declared or installed separately if needed.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] The TypeScript compiler, named `tsc`, is written in TypeScript.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] As a result, it can be compiled into regular JavaScript and can then be executed in any JavaScript engine (e.g. a browser).
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] The compiler package comes bundled with a script host that can execute the compiler.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] It is also available as a Node.js package that uses Node.js as a host.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] The compiler is currently being rewritten in Go for version 7.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] The compiler can *target* a given edition of ECMAScript (such as ECMAScript 5 for legacy browser compatibility), but by default compiles for the latest standards.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] Using plug-ins, TypeScript can be integrated with build automation tools, including Grunt (grunt-ts), Apache Maven (TypeScript Maven Plugin), Gulp (gulp-typescript) and Gradle (TypeScript Gradle Plugin).
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] TSLint scans TypeScript code for conformance to a set of standards and guidelines.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] ESLint, a standard JavaScript linter, also provided some support for TypeScript via community plugins.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] However, ESLint's inability to leverage TypeScript's language services precluded certain forms of semantic linting and program-wide analysis.
[src:adonisjs-node/typescript] In early 2019, the TSLint team announced the linter's deprecation in favor of `typescript-eslint`, a joint effort of the TSLint, ESLint and TypeScript teams to consolidate linting under the ESLint umbrella for improved performance, community unity and developer accessibility.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:adonisjs-node/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
